{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637540"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:44:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:44:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17669"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17669"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10383"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111771"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10383"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17669"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93839"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10476"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24271"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24306"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45528"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111771"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA solution containing sodium chloride is separated from pure water by a semipermeable membrane that allows only water molecules to pass through.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the direction of net water movement by osmosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["From high to low hydrostatic pressure","From low to high solute concentration","From high to low osmotic pressure","From high to low solute concentration","From low to high water concentration"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWater moves by osmosis \u003Cstrong\u003Efrom low to high solute concentration\u003C/strong\u003E. This movement occurs because water follows its concentration gradient, moving from where water molecules are more concentrated (pure water) to where they are less concentrated (sodium chloride solution). The presence of solutes reduces the concentration of water molecules in a solution.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom high to low hydrostatic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - Hydrostatic pressure affects bulk fluid flow (as in blood vessels) but does not drive osmosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom high to low osmotic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - Water actually moves toward areas of higher osmotic pressure. Osmotic pressure is the pressure needed to prevent water movement into a solution\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom high to low solute concentration\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the opposite of the correct direction of water movement\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom low to high water concentration\u003C/strong\u003E - Water moves from higher to lower water concentration, not the reverse\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis principle explains many biological processes including:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECell swelling in hypotonic solutions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECell shrinkage in hypertonic solutions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWater reabsorption in kidney tubules\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMaintenance of blood volume\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Osmosis is the movement of water across a semipermeable membrane from an area of low solute concentration to high solute concentration.","Water moves down its concentration gradient, from where water molecules are more concentrated to where they are less concentrated.","Osmotic pressure is the pressure required to prevent water movement into a solution with higher solute concentration."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93839"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17669"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93839"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-19T18:51:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-19T18:55:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10383"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111771"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt"